<div id="review_3308366704" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3308366704" />
    <a title="Aimee Baer Spears" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/106343426-aimee-baer-spears"><img alt="Aimee Baer Spears" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1600359156p2/106343426.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3308366704?book_show_action=true">Apr 03, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Aimee Baer Spears" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Aimee Baer Spears" href="/user/show/106343426-aimee-baer-spears">Aimee Baer Spears</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19860524-like-a-fire-is-burning">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/106343426-aimee-baer-spears?shelf=owned">owned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3308366704&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3308366704" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2130013660094114862">Overall, I did like this book very much, but for certain reasons (listed below), I couldn&apos;t give it more than 4 stars.<br/><br/>What I liked about the book...<br/>- I thought some chapters were well written and broke from the main narration style - for instance, ch. 18 was a chapter written completely as different letters written to different characters I thought that was very creative and a nice break from the usual narrative style.<br/>- Lots of different characters to keep track of; more of the Steed children ha</span>
  <span id="freeText2130013660094114862" style="display:none">Overall, I did like this book very much, but for certain reasons (listed below), I couldn't give it more than 4 stars.<br /><br />What I liked about the book...<br />- I thought some chapters were well written and broke from the main narration style - for instance, ch. 18 was a chapter written completely as different letters written to different characters I thought that was very creative and a nice break from the usual narrative style.<br />- Lots of different characters to keep track of; more of the Steed children have a voice or a part in the story (Melissa, for example). Also, it's nice to have a more equalized amount of male and female voices.<br />- Each character has certain trials and challenges to go through; the most interesting in my opinion were Lydia's, Melissa's, Jessica's, and Joshua's. It was hard to watch Nathan and Lydia's marriage struggle - they both love each other so much, but I think it goes to show that even with love for your s/o, marriage is still hard and you need to constantly work at it. When they finally listened to each others' needs, I felt like that was a big turning point and allowed for growth in their relationship that was super satisfying to read. <br />- It was interesting to see both sides of the story; though most of it was from the Saints' perspective, it was interesting to see things from an antagonist's POV (Joshua). <br />- My favorite part of the whole book was towards the end where Nathan confronts his father-in-law and shows him the "scars of his discipleship." That was probably the most heart-wrenching and also most powerful part of the book. <br /><br />Dislikes...<br />- I thought the story of this particular book in the series was longer than it needed to be. It felt in some places more of a nonfiction narrative than the storyline of the previous novel. It was long because of tangents included in Mormon history that maybe didn't need to be included for the sake of the story.<br />- It was hard to keep track of time. Some events were quickly a chapter might have a span of months or even years. Some had a shorter amount of time. It was just confusing, especially if you're not familiar with church history.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2130013660094114862" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

